===Etymology 1===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*ǵʰer-|id=yearn}}
The {{glossary|verb}} is derived from {{inh|en|enm|yernen}}, {{m|enm|yern|t=to express or feel desire; to desire, long or wish for; to lust after; to ask or demand for}}{{nb...|gern, ierne, yerne, yrne, ȝarne, ȝarnin, ȝarnon, ȝern, ȝerne, ȝernen, ȝiern, ȝirnin, ȝorn, ȝyrn, ȝyrne, (chiefly Northern English) gerne, giern, yarne, yhern, yherne, (Northwest Midlands) yurn, (Early Middle English) georne, geornen, gierne, girne, gyrne, ierne, irne, ȝeorne, ȝeornen, ȝeornnen, ȝernenn, ȝierne, ȝirnæn, ȝirn, ȝirne, ȝurn, ȝurne, (Early Middle English, Northern England) yhern, yherne, yiern, ȝarne, ȝherne, (Early Middle English, Southwest England) herne, ȝorne, ȝurn, ȝurne, (Early Middle English, Southwest Midlands) ȝeorne, ȝeornne, ȝirni, ȝurne|otherforms=1}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=yernen|pos=v|id=MED53910}}</ref> from {{inh|en|ang|ġeornan|t=to desire, yearn; to beg}}{{nb...|(chiefly Late Old English) iærnan, ieornan, gernan (rare), gurnan, (Old English) geornan, giernan, giornan (chiefly Northumbria), girnan, gyrnan, gyrnnan (rare)|otherforms=1}}, from {{inh|en|gmw-pro|*girnijan|t=to be eager for, desire}}, from {{inh|en|gem-pro|*girnijaną|t=to desire, want}}, from {{m|gem-pro|*gernaz|t=eager, willing}} (from {{der|en|ine-pro|*ǵʰer-|t=to yearn for}}) + {{m|gem-pro|*-janą|pos={{glossary|suffix}} forming {{glossary|factitive verb}}s from {{glossary|adjective}}s}}.<ref>Compare {{R:OED Online|pos=''v.''{{sup|1}}|noformat=1|id=231488|date=March 2021|nodot=1}}; {{R:Lexico|pos=v}}</ref>
The {{glossary|noun}} is derived from the verb.<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=n|id=231487|date=March 2018}}</ref>
====Verb====
{{en-verb}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|also|figuratively}} To have a [[strong#Adjective|strong]] [[desire#Noun|desire]] for something or to [[do#Verb|do]] something; to [[long#Verb|long]] for or to do something.
#: {{ux|en|All I '''yearn''' for is a simple life.}}
#* {{RQ:Beaumont Fletcher Comedies and Tragedies|title=Bonduca|act=II|scene=iv|page=56|column=2|passage=I muſt do that my heart-ſtrings '''yern''' to do: but my word's paſt.}}
#* {{RQ:Spectator|issue=142|date=13 August 1711|page=243|passage=You are now before my eyes, my eyes that are ready to flow with tenderness, but cannot give relief to my gushing heart, that dictates what I am now saying, and '''yearns''' to tell you all its achings.}}
#* {{RQ:Dickens Old Curiosity Shop|chapter=32|page=274|passage=By morning's cheerful glow, but oftener still by evening's gentle light, the child, with a respect for the short and happy intercourse of these two sisters which forbade her to approach and say a thankful word, although she '''yearned''' to do so, followed them at a distance in their walks and rambles, {{...}}}}
#* {{RQ:Kipling Captains Courageous|chapter=X|page=298|passage=What his soul '''yearned''' after was control of his father's newly purchased sailing-ship.}}
#* {{RQ:London When God Laughs|story=Just Meat|page=125|passage=And Jim supported his twitching body by holding on to the sink, the while he '''yearned''' toward the yellowish concoction that stood for life.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=E[dward] M[organ] Forster|authorlink=E. M. Forster|chapter=40|title=[[w:Maurice (novel)|Maurice]]|location=London|publisher={{w|Penguin Books}}|month=(writing and revisions)|year=1913–1960|year_published=1971 (1987 printing)|page=181|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/maurice00fors/page/181/mode/1up|isbn=978-0-14-003515-5|passage=But all that night his body '''yearned''' for Alec's, despite him. He called it lustful, a word easily uttered, and opposed it to his work, his family, his friends, his position in society. {{...}} But his body would not be convinced.}}
#* {{RQ:Montgomery Anne of the Island|chapter=Letters from Home|page=50|passage=Anne, please tell me over again that you like me a little bit. I '''yearn''' to hear it.}}
## {{lb|en|specifically}} To long for something in the [[past#Noun|past]] with [[melancholy]] or [[nostalgia]].
##* {{quote-book|en|author=Iris Murdoch|authorlink=Iris Murdoch|title={{w|An Accidental Man}}|location=New York, N.Y.|publisher={{w|Viking Press}}|year=1971|year_published=February 1972|page=420|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/accidentalman00murd/page/n429/mode/1up|isbn=978-0-670-10208-2|passage=If I don’t go now, thought Charlotte, I shall have lost a chance which I shall eternally regret and '''yearn''' after.}}
##* {{quote-book|en|author=J[ohn] M[axwell] Coetzee|authorlink=J. M. Coetzee|chapter=17|title={{w|Youth: Scenes from Provincial Life II}}|edition=1st American|location=London|publisher={{w|Vintage Books}}|year=2002|page=137|isbn=978-0-670-03102-3|passage=Having shaken the dust of the ugly new South Africa from his feet, is he '''yearning''' for the South Africa of the old days, when Eden was still possible?}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive}} Of [[music]], [[word#Noun|words]], etc.: to [[express#Verb|express]] strong desire or [[longing#Noun|longing]].
#* {{RQ:Keats Lamia|poem=The Eve of St. Agnes|stanza=VII|page=86|passage=The music, '''yearning''' like a God in pain, / She scarcely heard: {{...}}}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|dated}} To have strong [[feeling#Noun|feelings]] of [[affection]], [[love#Noun|love]], [[sympathy]], etc., toward someone.
#* {{RQ:King James Version|Genesis|43|30|page=126|column=1|passage=And [[w:Joseph (Genesis)|Joſeph]] made haſte: for his bowels did '''yerne''' upon his brother: and he ſought where to weepe, and hee entred into his chamber, & wept there.}}
#* {{RQ:Spectator|issue=123|date=21 July 1711|page=158|passage=I have left your mother in the next room. Her heart '''yearns''' towards you.}}
#* {{RQ:Reade Simpleton|volume=II|chapter=XII|pages=99–100|pageref=100|passage=Oh, it was a pretty sight to see this modest young creature, little more than a child herself, anticipating maternity, but blushing every now and then, and looking askant at her lord and master. How his very bowels '''yearned''' over her!}}
#* {{RQ:Henry Adams Democracy|chapter=III|page=52|passage={{...}} Mr. Ratcliffe’s heart '''yearned''' toward the charming girl quite with the sensations of a father, or even of an elder brother.}}
#* {{RQ:Schreiner African Farm|chapter=Tant’ Sannie Holds an Upsitting, and Gregory Writes a Letter|page=248|passage=But supper had cheered Tant' Sannie, who found it impossible longer to maintain that decorous silence, and whose heart '''yearned''' over the youth.}}
# {{lb|en|intransitive|obsolete}} To be [[distressed#Adjective|distressed]] or [[pained#Adjective|pained]]; to [[grieve]]; to [[mourn]].
#* {{RQ:Sterne Tristram Shandy|volume=II|chapter=XVII|page=144|passage=My father’s and my uncle ''Toby''’s hearts '''yearn’d''' with ſympathy for the poor fellow’s diſtreſs,—{{...}}}}
# {{lb|en|transitive}} ''Often followed by'' '''[[out]]''': to [[perform]] (music) which [[convey]]s or [[say#Verb|say]] (words) which express strong desire or longing.
# {{lb|en|transitive|archaic|or|poetic}} To have a strong desire or longing (for something or to do something).
#: {{synonyms|en|earn|q1=obsolete}}
# {{lb|en|transitive|obsolete}} To [[cause#Verb|cause]] (someone) to have strong feelings of affection, love, sympathy, etc.; also, to grieve or pain (someone).
#: {{synonyms|en|earn|q1=obsolete}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Merry Wives|act=III|scene=v|page=52|column=2|passage=Well, ſhe laments Sir for it, that it would '''yern''' your heart to see it: {{...}}}}
#* {{RQ:Shakespeare Henry 5|act=IV|scene=iii|page=86|column=2|passage=It '''yernes''' me not, if men my Garments weare; / Nor care I who doth feed vpon my coſt: / Such outward things dwell not in my deſires. / But if it be a ſinne to couet Honor, / I am the moſt offending Soule aliue.}}
#* {{quote-book|en|author=[William Hamilton Maxwell]|authorlink=William Hamilton Maxwell|chapter=Badger-hunting|title=The Field Book: Or, Sports and Pastimes of the United Kingdom;{{nb...|Compiled from the Best Authorities, Ancient and Modern.}}|location=London|publisher={{w|Effingham Wilson}}|year=1833|page=31|pageurl=https://archive.org/details/fieldbookorsport00maxw/page/31/mode/1up|column=2|oclc=57230597|passage=When the badger finds that the terriers '''yearn''' him in his burrow, he will stop the hole between him and the terriers; {{...}}}}
#* {{quote-journal|en|author=Leigh Hunt|title=A Pinch of Snuff (''Concluded.'')|magazine=Leigh Hunt’s London Journal|location=London|publisher=[[w:Charles Knight (publisher)|Charles Knight]],{{nb...|Ludgate Street}}; and Henry Hooper,{{nb...|Pall-Mall East.}}|date=25 June 1834|volume=I|issue=13|page=98|pageurl=https://books.google.com/books?id=OkjJ-KxKSVsC&pg=PA98|column=1|oclc=276731836|passage=Wants to sneeze and cannot do it! / Now it '''yearns''' me, thrills me, stings me, / Now with rapturous torment wrings me, / Now says “Sneeze, you fool; get through it.”}}
