===Etymology 2===
{{root|en|ine-pro|*h₃er-}}
Probably either:<ref>{{R:OED Online|pos=''v.''{{sup|2}}|noformat=1|id=231489|date=December 2020}}</ref>
* a variant of {{m|en|earn|t=to curdle, as milk}} (though this word is attested later), from {{inh|en|enm|erne}}, {{m|enm|ernen|t=to coagulate, congeal}} {{qualifier|chiefly South Midlands}} {{nb...|(chiefly Middle English from Southwest England and Southwest Midlands, and Early Middle English) eorne, eornen, herne, hurnen, uerne, urne, urnen, hurnen, (Early Middle English, Southwest Midlands) eærne, earnæ, heorne, hirnen, irne, irnen|otherforms=1}}, a {{glossary|metathetic}} variant of {{m|enm|rennen|t=to run; to coagulate, congeal}}, from {{inh|en|ang|rinnen|t=to run}} (with the variants {{m|ang|iernan}}, {{m|ang|irnan}}) and {{der|en|non|rinna|t=to move quickly, run; of liquid: to flow, run; to melt}},<ref>{{R:MED Online|entry=rennen|pos=''v.''(1)|noformat=1|id=MED36797}}</ref> both ultimately from {{der|en|ine-pro|*h₃er-|t=to move, stir; to rise, spring}}; or
* a {{back-formation|en|yearning|t=(''Scotland, archaic'') rennet; calf (or other animal’s) stomach used to make rennet|nocap=1}}.
